## What to try next (without me)

You have everything you need to do this again, alone. A few starting points roughly ordered by lift:

1. **Iterate on what you just shipped.** Open the repo in your editor, change a label, change a color, add a field. Commit. Push. Refresh your URL 60 seconds later. You'll see the change. That feedback loop is the whole game.
2. **Build a second small thing.** Same template, different problem (or different person, if you came in via the person-shaped path). Whatever you build, it'll go faster the second time. That's the signal that the rails came off.
3. **Build with a different template.** If you used `<<template>>` first, try one of the other two next. The folder structure and the deploy story are identical; only the bending surfaces change.
<!-- IF path=problem-shaped -->
4. **Tell Claude Code what you want without the interview.** Open a new folder, run `claude`, and describe what you want in one paragraph. See how close it gets without the 7 questions. That comparison will teach you more about how to talk to Claude than any tutorial will.
<!-- ENDIF -->
<!-- IF path=person-shaped -->
4. **Try the other path.** You came in via "Surprise me" — next time, try the problem-shaped interview by saying yes when `/first-build` asks if you have something specific in mind. Same skill, sharper output when you already know what you want.
<!-- ENDIF -->

When you get stuck, the answer is almost never "I need a better tool." It's usually "I haven't told Claude enough about what I want." Re-read your `spec.md` — that level of specificity is the unlock.

